			<title>USA: Lesbian teen abused even by teachers, forced to use boys toilets.</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76247-USA-Lesbian-teen-abused-even-by-teachers-forced-to-use-boys-toilets&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 21 Dec 2013 15:10:56 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>http://www.addictinginfo.org/2013/12/19/lesbian-sues-ms-school-district/ 
 
 
---Quote--- 
School Bullies ‘Lesbo Dyke-@ss Freak,’ Forces Her To Use Boys’ Bathroom (VIDEO) 
 
Author: Elisabeth Parker December 19, 2013 12:28 pm</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="http://www.addictinginfo.org/2013/12/19/lesbian-sues-ms-school-district/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.addictinginfo.org/2013/12...hool-district/</a><br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			School Bullies ‘Lesbo Dyke-@ss Freak,’ Forces Her To Use Boys’ Bathroom (VIDEO)<br />
<br />
Author: Elisabeth Parker December 19, 2013 12:28 pm <br />
<br />
<br />
  <br />
<br />
 <br />
 <br />
<br />
Lesbian teen bullied, forced to use boys' room, sues school district. Photo of Destin Holmes.<br />
Teachers and students bullied this lesbian teen ‘to the point of suicide,’ called her vile names, and forced her to use the boys’ bathroom. Now she’s suing. Photo of Destin Holmes screen captured from WLOX 13 News footage.<br />
<br />
Teachers and students bullied this lesbian teen “to the point of suicide.”<br />
<br />
When will people learn that bullying children is NEVER okay? Teachers and students bullied this lesbian teen “to the point of suicide,” called her vile names, and forced her to use the boys’ bathroom. Now she’s suing. WLOX 13 News reports that the Southern Poverty Law Center (SPLC) has filed a federal lawsuit against the Moss Point School District in Mississippi on behalf of Destin Holmes, a lesbian high school student.<br />
<br />
WLOX 13 News’ on-air broadcast (shown below) adds that Holmes’ schoolmates cruelly taunted her with anti-lesbian epithets like, “dyke,” “lesbo” and “dyke-ass freak.” Her teachers behaved even worse. One made her use the boys’ bathroom. Another teacher had the lesbian teen come in for a “talk” during which Holmes was called a “pathetic fool,” and told “I don’t want a dyke in this school.”<br />
<br />
<br />
“My grades sucked, because it was hard to concentrate with them calling you a freak, and a dyke and a lesbian.”<br />
 – Destin Holmes, on why she’s suing her school district.<br />
<br />
Anjali Nair, a lawyer from the SPLC adds:<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
“Destin suffered from severe, pervasive harassment from students, teachers, and administrators in the district on account of her sexual orientation,”<br />
<br />
Here’s the video, with WLOX 13 News’ report on the SPLC’s lawsuit on behalf of this lesbian teen.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
The school district was warned. Now their lesbian teen is fighting back.<br />
<br />
The anti-lesbian bullying started in the 2011-12 school year when Holmes was in middle school. Her parents took her out, home schooled her for a year, then re-enrolled her in high school this year. Alas, the high school’s climate for lesbians was no better than the one in middle school. WLOX 13 News explains that the Moss Point School District had ample warning that this lawsuit was coming. Back in March, the SPLC sent a letter demanding that the district change school policies to protect the civil rights of their lesbian, gay, bi, and transgender students and keep them safe. The school district made no attempt to comply, so the SPLC filed a lawsuit. Nair told WLOX 13 News.<br />
<br />
<br />
“After sending the school district a demand letter in March of 2013, that they take steps to prevent and end the bullying and harassment within the school district, we were not able to reach a resolution to guarantee the safety of students like Destin.”<br />
<br />
The lawsuit demands that a stronger set of anti-bullying measures to be put in place, and also seeks money to cover all the damage suffered by Holmes and her parents due to the constant anti-lesbian bullying.<br />
<br />
And what does Destin Holmes have to say about all of this?<br />
<br />
When asked about the anti-lesbian bullying and what Destin Holmes wants from her teachers and classmates in school, Holmes answered that she wants them to:<br />
<br />
“Open up their mind and realize you don’t need to bully somebody just because they want to date girls or they want to be gay, or they want to be lesbian, or bi, or a transgender. I’m hoping it will just stop.”<br />
<br />
Here at AI, we’d like people to “open up their minds” too. We’d also like people to stop bullying children. Lesbian teens aren’t the only kids who suffer from bullies and the adults who  condone them. We like to think this sort of thing only happens in the deep south, but the fact is, it’s happening all over the country.<br />
&#9726;An autistic teen from Des Moines, IA was bullied at school, and the parents and teachers said the poor kid deserved it.<br />
&#9726;A seven-year-old black girl from Tulsa, OK was sent home from school because her hair was too “distracting.”<br />
&#9726;A Florida teen killed herself after being bullied online by her schoolmates and told that she should “drink bleach and die.”<br />
&#9726;A Texas school snatched away a 12-year-old boy’s lunch, and threw it in the garbage because he didn’t have 30 cents to pay for it.<br />
&#9726;A high school football coach in Utah found out that his players had bullied other students and suspended the entire team. This is one of the few cases where meanness was not condoned by the adults.<br />
&#9726;A Texas school banned its Latino students from speaking Spanish while on school grounds.<br />
&#9726;A 13-year-old boy from Kansas was kicked out of school for wearing a purse.<br />
<br />
Our nation’s children have a legal right to get an education and to be safe at school. It’s sad that the only way to ensure that schools don’t treat children badly is to slap them with costly lawsuits.
			
		<hr />
	</div>
