			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>from disagreement with Ppatty in another thread<br />
<br />
No, I do not think Biggs was a &quot;hero&quot;, he was a petty crook, who should have got 5 to 15 years<br />
but, the great Train Robbers WERE unduly punished, because the Establishment bastards wanted to put the screws down on &quot;little folk&quot; who dared mess with the &quot;power of the state&quot;<br />
<br />
So, they got handed 30 year jail sentences, a complete perversion of the judicial process and THAT was utter f'ing bullshit.<br />
The robbers committed a serious crime, one guard was coshed left with a head injury, all of which merits as said, 5 to 15 years<br />
Instead they got hit with 30 years, a murder penalty!<br />
<br />
Then when Biggs came back to the UK, even in poor health, they were determined to get their &quot;pound of flesh&quot; and kept him in jail when he was suffering.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, I have no love for scumbags, but Biggs was NOT one of the &quot;cosh&quot; men, and was a very minor player, who spent much of the robbery sitting at the sidelines cause the train driver friend he'd brought couldn't run the train they'd hijacked<br />
yet he spent more time in jail than any of them.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			The 11 men sentenced all felt aggrieved at the sentences handed down, particularly Bill Boal (who died in prison) and Lennie Field, who were later found not guilty of the charges against them. The other men (aside from Wheater) resented what they considered to be the excessive length of the sentences, which were longer than those given to many murderers or armed robbers at the time. <br />
At that period, there was no parole system in place and prisoners served the full term of the sentence. Train robbers who were sentenced later, and by different judges, received shorter terms.<br />
<br />
<br />
John Thomas Daly age 32 antiques dealer N/A—No Case to Answer <br />
Ronald Arthur Biggs age 34 carpenter 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Douglas Gordon Goody age 34 hairdresser 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Charles Frederick Wilson age 31 market trader 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Thomas William Wisbey age 34 bookmaker 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Robert Welch age 34 club proprietor 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
James Hussey age 34 painter 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Roy John James age 28 racing motorist and silversmith 30 years (25 years for conspiracy to rob and 30 years for armed robbery) <br />
Roger John Cordrey age 42 florist 20 years (20 years for conspiracy to rob and various receiving stolen goods charges) <br />
Brian Arthur Field age 29 solicitor's clerk 25 years (20 years for Conspiracy to rob and 5 years for obstructing justice) <br />
Leonard Denis Field age 31 merchant seaman 25 years (20 years for Conspiracy to rob and 5 years for obstructing justice) <br />
John Denby Wheater age 41 solicitor 3 years <br />
William Gerald Boal age 50 engineer 24 years <br />
<br />
<br />
Ronnie Biggs[edit]<br />
<br />
Biggs received a 30-year sentence following the robbery and served 15 months before escaping. He fled to Paris, where he acquired new identity papers and underwent plastic surgery. In 1970, he quietly moved to Adelaide, Australia, where he worked as a builder and lived a relatively normal life. He was tipped off by persons unknown and moved to Melbourne, later escaping to Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, after police discovered his Melbourne address. Biggs could not be extradited because there was no extradition treaty between Britain and Brazil, a condition for the Brazilian process of extradition. Additionally, he became father to a Brazilian son, which afforded him legal immunity since the father of a Brazilian minor can not be extradited from Brazil. As a result, he lived openly in Rio for many years, safe from the British authorities. In 1981, Biggs's Brazilian son became a member of a successful band Turma do Balão Mágico, bringing a new source of income to his father. In a short time, however, the band faded into obscurity and dissolved, leaving father and son relatively short of funds again.<br />
<br />
In May 2001, aged 71 and having suffered three strokes, Biggs voluntarily returned to England. His son, Michael Biggs, said in a press release[42] that, contrary to some press reports, Biggs had not returned to the UK simply to receive free health care. According to Michael, health care was available in Brazil and he had many friends and supporters who would certainly have contributed to any such expenses. Biggs's stated desire was to &quot;walk into a Margate pub as an Englishman and buy a pint of bitter&quot;.[43] Biggs was aware that he would be arrested and jailed. After detention and a short court hearing he was sent back to prison to serve the remainder of his sentence. He served another 8 years of his sentence.<br />
<br />
On 2 July 2009, Biggs was denied parole by Justice Secretary Jack Straw, who considered Biggs to be still &quot;wholly unrepentant.&quot;[44] Biggs has stated that the 30-year term was &quot;out of order&quot;[45] for the crime committed, and that is why he planned an escape.<br />
<br />
On 6 August 2009, Biggs was granted release from prison on &quot;compassionate grounds&quot; due to a severe case of pneumonia, after serving only part of the sentence imposed at trial.[46] Michael Biggs has said publicly that his father expressed remorse for the robbery, but not for his life on the run. By the time he was released he had served more jail time than any of the robbers, despite his relatively minor role.<br />
<br />
Since his release Biggs has updated his autobiography, Odd Man Out: The Last Straw (2011) (ISBN 978-0-9570398-2-7), which explains his role in the robbery and his life story. In 2013 Biggs contributed, along with Bruce Reynolds, to The Great Train Robbery 50th Anniversary:1963-2013 (2013) (ISBN 0957255977), a publication that gave the most detailed account yet of the planning and execution of the robbery, and debunked many of the myths and legends surrounding the event.<br />
<br />
Biggs died at the Carlton Court Care home, London, aged 84, on the early morning of Wednesday 18 December 2013.<br />
<br />
			
		<hr />
